## **Bob's Thought Process:**

Bob knows Alice wants to kill Orim. He has no cards in hand, so he can't counter the Kindles or use other damage prevention.

But he **can** use Orim's ability **once per turn**.

So his optimal play is to **use Orim's ability to prevent the first Kindle's damage**.

That way, he **saves Orim** for the second Kindle.

But wait—**he can't**. Because if he uses Orim's ability to prevent the first 2 damage, then Orim is tapped, and he can't use it again.

But if he **doesn't** use the ability, then the first Kindle will deal 2 damage to Orim, and Orim will be at 1/3.

Then the second Kindle will deal 3 damage, and Orim will die.

So Bob's **only option** is to **use Orim's ability to prevent the first 2 damage**.

But that's still a **loss**—he can't prevent the second 3 damage.

So Bob's **optimal play** is to **tap Orim to prevent the first 2 damage**.

